Mr. Leddy recently retired as the Chief Executive Officer of Verizon Telematics, Inc. (f.k.a. Hughes Telematics). Verizon Telematics is the leading provider of full service connected services to the automobile industry providing services to both factory equipped vehicles and aftermarket vehicles. Mr. Leddy was the founder of Hughes Telematics in 2006 and provided executive leadership in the development of the company’s strategic vision and implementation of its connected car services. Mr. Leddy served as a member of its board of directors since the inception and as the Chief Executive Officer from December 2006.
From June 2002 through December 2006, Mr. Leddy served as Chief Executive Officer and President of SkyTerra Communications, Inc. (SkyTerra). From September 1980 to December 2001, Mr. Leddy worked for EMS Technologies serving as its President for many of those years. Mr. Leddy presently serves on the board of directors for Global Eagle Entertainment. From 2005 to 2011, Mr. Leddy served on the board of directors of Hughes Communications, Inc. From 2006 to 2008, Mr. Leddy served on the board of directors of SkyTerra. Mr. Leddy received his bachelor’s degree in Physics from the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta, Georgia and a master’s degree in Electrical Engineering from Stanford University.


Jim is a proven security leader with over two decades of information security experience.
He has a history of outstanding performance and growth, business turnarounds, and global recognition for innovation in security strategies and execution.
Jim is a published, internationally-recognized expert on information security. He is currently with Optiv as the VP and GM of their security programs. Prior to Optiv he was with HP as the Global Security Practice Head and with British Telecom as the VP of Security Services for North America and the VP of Ethical Hacking for BT.
Prior to that was the Chief Security Officer for International Network Services, where he created the highest NSA rated professional security services organization in the world. From 1999 to 2002, he worked at Bell Labs for the advancement of security technologies. With Bell Labs, he led the development of a communications systems security architecture that resulted in a patent and is the X.805 ITU standard.
Jim is based on North Carolina with his family and is a contributor to the Green Beret Foundation and H3 in support of our wounded, ill, and injured warriors.







 
  

